cing the affective contours of documented and undocumented immigrants' experiences and the Church's multiple postures toward transnational migration, she shows how different ways of being Catholic inform constructions of gender, labor, and sexuality whose fault lines intersect across contemporary Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aChurch and statexCatholic Church. 0aChurch and state; Catholic Church. 0aEmigration and immigrationxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aEmigration and immigration; Religious aspects; Catholic Church. 0aLatin AmericansxMigrationsxHistory. 0aLatin Americans; Migrations; History. 0aTransnationalismxHistory. 0aTransnationalism; History. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh  aAffects.  aBenedict XVI.  aGender.  aLatin America.  aLegionaires of Christ.  aMexico.  aMigration.  aReturn of Missions.  aRome.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311072902308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016z978311071186840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823267514zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823267514423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823267514.jpg  a978-3-11-071186-8  NYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-072902-3  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK